What you need to know:

Gladys has created her oasis by harvesting and storing millions of litres of rainwater, which she uses to irrigate her crops. Butternuts thrive in well-drained soils and in warm regions. To plant the crop, one needs to prepare the seedbed thoroughly. Gladys harvested two tonnes of squash from a quarter acre recently, with the crop maturing after three months.Erik Nielsen, a rainwater harvesting specialist, notes that farm ponds are among the most sustainable low-cost methods of collecting water.